## ✅ Index Creation Complete

### Pre-flight checks
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Table rows | ~500 million |
| Existing indexes | `orders_pkey` on `id` only |
| `user_id` index already exists? | ❌ No — safe to create |

### What was done
- Used **`CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`** — the only safe method for a 500M-row table with 24/7 writes
- **No `BEGIN`/`COMMIT` transaction wrapper** — required for `CONCURRENTLY` to work
- Lock acquired: `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking — INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE continued uninterrupted throughout)
- Build time: ~180 seconds (expected trade-off vs. the instant-but-blocking standard `CREATE INDEX`)

### Post-creation verification
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Index `idx_orders_user_id` present | ✅ Confirmed |
| Index type | B-Tree on `user_id` |
| Active lock conflicts on `orders` | ✅ None |

### What was avoided
- ❌ `CREATE INDEX` (without `CONCURRENTLY`) — would have held an `AccessExclusiveLock` for 10–30 minutes, freezing all order writes site-wide
- ❌ Wrapping in a transaction block — would have caused `CONCURRENTLY` to fail
- ❌ Duplicate index creation — verified first

`user_id` queries on `orders` should now resolve in milliseconds instead of 10+ seconds.
